text: Alea iacta est is a Latin phrase that means "the die is cast (thrown)". Suetonius credits Julius Caesar as having said it on January 10, 49 B.C when he led his army across the Rubicon river in Northern Italy. It means things have happened that can't be changed back. == In other languages == The phrase, either in Latin or in translation, is used in many different languages. * * * * * * * * * , and, * , and, * * * * * Indonesian: Nasi sudah menjadi bubur (lit. rice has become porridge) * * * * * * * * * * * * * * Category:Latin phrases
